\n\nKundan is one of the oldest methods of traditional jewelry making in India dating back to the Mughal era. Kundan is pure gold and Meena is the process of enameling. Kundan Meena jewelry pieces have encrusted gemstones on one side and smooth decorated colored surfaces on the other. This kind of jewelry making involves setting a precious stone such as a diamond, sapphire or ruby on its mount using a gold foil.\n\nMost of the intricate Kundan Meena jewelry is made by skilled artisans, which adds to the value of the pieces. The designs are simple yet aesthetic, consisting of simple geometric patterns to more elaborate embellishments. One standout feature of most Kundan Meena jewelry pieces is that they are colorful and eye-catching. Regardless of whether a precious or semi-precious gem is used, the finished product looks beautiful and sophisticated.\n\n <strong>How Kundan Meena jewelry is made</strong>\n\nThe process of Kundan Meena jewelry making first involves preparing the gold foil. The gold is made soft and malleable after passing it through a rolling machine that churns out flat sheets of 22 carat. The resulting gold sheet is hammered and beaten to get the required thickness.\n\nAfter the soft gold sheet is ready, the artisans carve the desired gold design with their hands or using tweezers. The resulting pattern forms the outer walls of the finished jewelry piece. The number of designs that have to be carved out depend on the type and size of the piece under making. After the gold designs have been fashioned out of the gold foil, they are bonded or soldered together to form the final shape of the jewelry piece. The soldering is done traditionally by puffing fire out of pipes onto the gold pieces and combining them into one solid piece, such as an earring or a necklace.\n\nThe black residue on the jewelry piece after the soldering process is cleaned using mild chemicals and then dried. After this, the piece is handed over to the gem setter. In gem setting, first the lac is heated and poured into the creek, which is supposed to hold the gem. Meanwhile the gem or stone that has to be encrusted is prepared. A gold or silver foil is fixed to the back of the gem to make it gleam. The gemstones are now placed into the creeks or holders.\n\n In the final step, the bits of 24 carat gold foils or kundan are set into the sides of the gemstones till they grip on tightly. In the Meenakari process, which is intricate and laborious, enamel colors are added to the jewelry piece through an engraving and fusing technique.\n\n Every Indian bride dreams of wearing a one-of-a-kind Kundan Meena jewelry set these days. After exquisite Kundan Meena pieces worn by Aishwarya Rai in the Bollywood epic Jodha Akbar caught the publics fancy, many jewelry showrooms in India have seen a rise in sales of Kundan Meena jewelry. Traditional handcrafted jewelry such as Kundan Meena has been cherished for centuries in India and is now finding popularity world over.","The Making of Kundan Meena Jewelry","","inherit","open","open","","52-revision-2","","","2011-01-25 15:47:03","2011-01-25 15:47:03","","52","http://www.nethaat.com/blog/?p=54","0","revision","","0");
