\n\nAlthough the festival of Holi is celebrated all over India, it is in Mathura, Nandagaon and other places associated with the legend of Krishna that the festivities gain a special sparkle. There is reason for this- Holi is closely linked with the divine love that the gopika Radha bore for the divine child Krishna.\n\n<strong>The Krishna folklore</strong>\n\nFolklore tells of how little Krishna compared himself with the fair skinned Radha and was unhappy about his dark complexion. Hearing him complain, mother Yashoda teasingly suggested that Krishna take colours of his choice and drench Radha in them so that her skin would be exactly the colour he wished it to be.\n\nIt is believed that little Krishna celebrated the first Holi on earth by applying all manner of colours on Radha and her gopika friends. Ever since, boys and girls, men and women gather on Holi day armed with powdered colours and coloured water to celebrate the occasion of the divine Krishna playing with colours with his beloved gopis.\n\n<strong>Holi gifts based on Krishna theme</strong>\n\nSince Holi is so closely associated with Krishna, it is appropriate that you choose a gift for the occasion that reminds one of this divine child. Wall hangings, pictures, paintings, even figurines of Krishna or the divine couple Radha- Krishna are the most fitting for this occasion.\n\n[caption id=\"attachment_144\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"240\" caption=\"Holi- Festival of colors \"]<a href=\"http://www.nethaat.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/1.2.jpg\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-144\" title=\"1.2\" src=\"http://www.nethaat.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/1.2.jpg\" alt=\"Holi- Festival of colors  \" width=\"240\" height=\"160\" /></a>[/caption]\n\nThere are many Indian traditional art forms such as Patachitra, Madhubani and Kalamkari that use Krishna as the main theme. The elongated features of the characters, vibrant colour palette of green, blue, red, black, yellow and white create a stunning representation of Krishna in the midst of gopis. There are many depictions of Rasa-Lila in these and other traditional hand made art forms that make perfect gifts for Holi. Choosing an intricate hand made art piece shows that you are willing to make an extra effort to find the perfect present for your loved ones. The recipient will surely appreciate the time and care you have expended in choosing such a special gift.\n\nOther than these, brass figurines of Krishna and Radha are all time favourite gift items that never go out of style. Such figurines can be an appropriate gift for a close family member, a business partner or a non Indian acquaintance.\n\nFor those who want a simpler and more fun gift idea, dry fruit plus Holi colours combo gift boxes are the best. These gift boxes are a good way to entice the receiver into an impromptu colour fest to truly capture the effervescent spirit of Krishna during the festival of colours.<strong> </strong>","Best Holi Gifts - The Krishna Connection","","publish","open","open","","best-holi-gifts-the-krishna-connection","","","2011-03-16 10:38:28","2011-03-16 10:38:28","","0","http://www.nethaat.com/blog/?p=142","0","post","","0");
